        Parameters:
        _vector - the vector to add to this vector.
        Returns:
        a new vector containing the element-by-element sum of this instance and the given vector.

      • getEpsilon

        int getEpsilon()
        Returns the value of epsilon used by this instance. Epsilon is the amount that two values may differ when compared, and still be considered equal. It is a technique used to get around the inexact representation of numbers with double precision floating point; otherwise, many comparisons expected to be equal would instead appear to be unequal. The value of epsilon is expressed in ulps (Units in the Last Place), which are the magnitude of the LSB of a floating point number.
        Returns:
        the value of epsilon for this vector

        Returns:
        the length of this vector

      • multiply

        Vector multiply(double _multiplier)
        Returns a new vector whose element values are this vector's element values multiplied by the given multiplier, element-by-element. The vector implementation class of the result is the same as that of this instance. In other words, X[n] = T[n] * m, where X is the returned vector, T is this vector, m is the given multiplier, and n is the set of all index values 0 .. T.length - 1.
        Parameters:
        _multiplier - the multiplier
        Returns:
        a new vector that is the multiple of this vector, using the given multiplier

      • subVector

        Vector subVector(int _start,
                 int _end)
        Returns a vector that is a contiguous subvector of this vector. The given start index must be a valid index for this vector, and the value at the start index will be the first value in the returned vector. The given end index must be in the range of t .. l, where t is the start index + 1, and l is the length of this vector. The length of the returned vector is equal to start - end. Throws an IndexOutOfBoundsException if either the given start or end indices are out of bounds.
        Parameters:
        _start - the start index within this vector for the returned vector
        _end - the end index within this vector for the returned vector
        Returns:
        the subvector

      • toArray

        double[] toArray()
        Returns an ordinary array containing the values of all the elements of this instance (both zero or empty values and nonzero or set values). The size of the array is equal to the length of this vector.
        Returns:
        the array containing all the values of this vector

      • toJaVector

        JaVector toJaVector()
        Returns a JaVector instance that is exactly equivalent to this vector. If this vector is an instance of JaVector, then this vector is simply returned. Otherwise a new instance of JaVector is created that is a copy of this vector. The resulting vector will compare with this vector as equal using the equals() method on either instance, and the result of hashCode() for each will be the same.
        Returns:
        a JaVector equivalent to this vector

      • iterator

        VectorIterator iterator(IteratorMode _iteratorMode)
        Returns a vector iterator over this vector's elements in the given mode. There are two aspects to the mode, each of which has two possibilities - so there are four possible combinations of modes.
        • Ordered or unordered: an ordered iterator returns values in index order (though if the iterator is also sparse, some indices may be skipped). An unordered iterator returns values in an unspecified order, not necessarily predictable, and possibly the same as when ordered.
        • Dense or sparse: A dense iterator iterates over all elements in the vector, whether set (nonzero) or empty (zero). a sparse iterator iterates over only the set (nonzero) elements.
        Parameters:
        _iteratorMode - the mode for this iterator: ordered or unordered, dense or sparse
        Returns:
        the iterator over this vector's elements in the given mode

      • hashCode

        int hashCode()
        Returns the hash code for this instance. Note that the hash code is identical for all implementations of Vector, and is based on all non-zero elements, their indices, and the epsilon. Other implementation-dependent properties are not included in the hash code.
        Overrides:
        hashCode in class java.lang.Object
        Returns:
        the hash code for this vector.
